04472nam a22006855i 9780824865399DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t19981998hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248653997 a10.1515/97808248653992doi  a(DE-B1597)484088  a(OCoLC)923486378  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHQ1764.N3bT35 1998eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.42/0952/1632211 aTamanoi, Mariko Asano, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnder the Shadow of Nationalism :bPolitics and Poetics of Rural Japanese Women /cMariko Asano Tamanoi. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: Japanese Nationalism and Rural Women -- t2. Fieldwork -- t3. Komori -- t4. Factory Women -- t5. The Countryside and the City 1: Yanagita Kunio and Japanese Native Ethnology -- t6. The Countryside and the City 2: Agrarianism among Nagano Middling Farmers -- t7. The Wartime Period -- t8. The Postwar "Democracy'' and the Post-postwar Nationalism -- tEpilogue: A Short Critique of the Notion ofidentity -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contribution of rural women to the creation and expansion of the Japanese nation-state is undeniable. As early as the nineteenth century, the women of central Japan's Nagano prefecture in particular provided abundant and cheap labor for a number of industries, most notably the silk spinning industry. Rural women from Nagano could also be found working, from a very young age, as nursemaids, domestic servants, and farm laborers. In whatever capacity they worked, these women became the objects of scrutiny and reform in a variety of nationalist discourses--not only because of the importance of their labor to the nation, but also because of their gender and domicile (the countryside was the centerpiece of state ideology and practice before and during the war, during the Occupation, and beyond). Under the Shadow of Nationalism explores the interconnectedness of nationalism and gender in the context of modern Japan. It combines the author's long-term field research with a painstaking examination of the documents behind these discourses produced at various levels of society, from the national (government records, social reformers' reports, ethnographic data) to the local (teachers' manuals, labor activists' accounts, village newspapers). It provides a wide-ranging yet in-depth look at a key group of Japanese women as national subjects through the critical chapters of Japanese modernity and postmodernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRural womenzJapanzNagano-kenxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in rural developmentzJapanzNagano-kenxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486539940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824865399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824865399/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK